1. Snappy
2. lzo
3. gzip
4. bzip2

Some of the compression codec are optimized for storge.
Some of the compression codec are optimized for speed.

Trade Off
If we want more compreesion ratio then we have to spend more time on compression.

1. Snappy
	It is very fast compression codec
	And in terms of compression it is not very good.
	Optimized for speed not for storage.
	It is not by default spittable.

avro,parquet,orc - container based file format

2. lzo
	It optimized for speed like snappy.
	It is by-default it spittable.

3. gzip
	It optimizsed for storage not for speed.
	It will provide 2.5 times better compression than snappy.
	It is not by default spittable.
	
4. bzip2
	It is optimised for storage and it is very-very slow.
	It is by-default it spittable.
	It normally  compress 9% better than Gzip but it is 10 times slowe than gzip.
	It is idally for archival purpose only.

More compresion means fewer blocks. And that leds to fever task to process the data.So it will take more time to process same amount of data.

consider you have 1 gb file before compression so task should be 8.
But after compression if it is 200 mb than only 2 task will run and processing time will increase.
	





| File Format | Supports Compression | Recommended Codec      |
| ----------- | -------------------- | ---------------------- |
| Parquet     | Yes                  | Snappy (default), Gzip |
| ORC         | Yes                  | Zlib, Snappy           |
| Avro        | Yes                  | Snappy, Deflate        |


| Codec      | Typical Compression Ratio | Example: 1 GB Uncompressed → | Notes                              |
| ---------- | ------------------------- | ---------------------------- | ---------------------------------- |
| **Gzip**   | **2.5x – 3.5x**           | \~300–400 MB                 | Best storage savings, but slow     |
| **LZO**    | 1.5x – 2.5x               | \~400–600 MB                 | Faster than Gzip, less compression |
| **Snappy** | **1.2x – 2x**             | \~500–800 MB                 | Very fast, low compression         |

